  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Identifying potential suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing internal AML compliance programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial activities\n- Identifying potential money laundering patterns\n- Implementing automated monitoring systems\n\n5. Training\n- Providing ongoing staff training on AML procedures\n- Ensuring employees understand detection techniques\n- Staying updated on regulatory changes\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant legal penalties, including:\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Revocation of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
